ile ignoring a sense of what integrity requires? Integrity and conscience are often thought to be closely related, perhaps even different aspects of a single impulse. This timely book supports a different and more complicated view. Acting with integrity and obeying one's conscience might be mutually reinforcing in some settings, but in others they can live in varying degrees of mutual tension. Bringing together prominent scholars of legal theory and political philosophy, the volume addresses both classic ruminations on integrity and conscience by Plato, Hume, and Kant as well as more contemporary examinations of professional ethics and the complex relations among politics, law and personal morality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Essays.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDyzenhaus, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraber, Mark A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenawalt, Kent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Thomas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKane, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKateb, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiss, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcconnell, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPierce Wells, Catharine, econ